'''Sander Gard Bolin Berge''' (born 14 February 1998) is a Norwegian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defensive midfielder]] for {{English football updater|Fulham}} club [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] and the [[Norway national football team|Norway national team]].

==Club career==
===Early career===
[[File:FC Salzburg gegen KRC Genk (UEFA Championsleague 17. September 2019) 16 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|200px|Berge training with [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]] in 2019.]]

Berge was born in [[Bærum]], Akershus.<ref name="Soccerway"/> He started his career playing youth football for [[Asker Fotball|Asker]], making his senior debut in the end of the 2013 season for the team then playing in the Norwegian [[2. divisjon]]. He joined top flight team [[Vålerenga Fotball|Vålerenga]] before the [[2015 Tippeligaen|2015 season]] and made his debut at the age of 17, scoring the opening goal of an 8–0 win over [[Lokomotiv Oslo]] in the first round of the [[Norwegian Football Cup|Norwegian Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogg.tv2.no/pl-kasperwikestad/2018/10/03/en-kjempetabbe-og-et-supertalent/|title=En kjempetabbe og et supertalent|language=no|date=3 October 2018|website=TV2}}</ref>

Berge made his [[Eliteserien|league]] debut for Vålerenga as a substitute against [[Sandefjord Fotball|Sandefjord]] on 11 July 2015 and his first league start against [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]] on 16 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aftenposten.no/sport/fotball/i/dOvdlJ/rosenborg-naadeloese-mot-vaalerengas-ti-menn|title=Rosenborg nådeløse mot Vålerengas ti menn|language=no|date=16 August 2016|website=Aftenspost}}</ref> He became established as a regular starter in the [[2016 Tippeligaen|2016 season]] and was named as the Norwegian league's [[Kniksen Award|young player of the year]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dagsavisen.no/sport/2016/12/23/sander-berge-kan-havne-i-belgia/|title=Sander Berge kan havne i Belgia|language=no|date=23 December 2016|website=Dagsavisen}}</ref>

On 2 January 2017, he signed a four-year contract with [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]]. He made his first team league debut on 21 January as a substitute in the 1–0 win away against [[K.A.S. Eupen|Eupen]]. He earned his first start and full match against [[Royal Excel Mouscron|Mouscron]] on 17 February in a 1–0 win at home, becoming an integral part of the team for the remaining season, which included an impressive run in the [[Europa League]], ending in the quarter finals against [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whoscored.com/Players/321020/Fixtures/Sander-Berge |title=Sander Berge|website=Whoscored.com|access-date=5 July 2022}}</ref>

During the [[2018–19 K.R.C. Genk season|2018–19 season]], Berge made 28 appearances as Genk won the [[2018–19 Belgian First Division A|Belgian championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/1759710/2020/04/28/sander-berge-best-position-sheffield-united-chris-wilder-norway/|title=What is Berge's best position and how can Wilder get the best out of him?|date=28 April 2020|website=The Athletic}}</ref>

Berge made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut in a 6–2 loss to [[RB Salzburg]] on 17 September 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tv.vg.no/video/185973/berge-om-haaland-ydmykelsen-pinlig|title=Berge om Haaland-ydmykelsen: – Pinlig|language=no|date=9 October 2019|website=Verdens Gang}}</ref> On 30 December, he was named by [[UEFA]] in the Champions League breakthrough team for 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/025a-0e9f8ded0e4a-52bbb4b4d605-1000--champions-league-breakthrough-team-of-2019/|title=Champions League breakthrough team of 2019|date=30 December 2019|publisher=UEFA}}</ref>

===Sheffield United===
On 30 January 2020, Berge signed for [[Premier League]] club [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], becoming the club's record signing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/SheffieldUnited/status/1222929277534031872|title=Twitter|publisher=Sheffield United F.C. |via=Twitter |access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=June 2025}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sufc.co.uk/news/2020/january/sander-berge-signs/|title=Record signing arrives at the Lane|date=30 January 2020 |publisher=Sheffield United F.C.|access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref> He joined on a four-and-a-half-year contract.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/jan/30/sheffield-united-sign-sander-berge-club-record-fee|title=Sheffield United break club transfer record to sign Sander Berge from Genk|date=30 January 2020|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref> On 2 July 2020, Berge scored his first goal for Sheffield United in a 3–1 win against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=2 July 2020|title=Sheffield United 3–1 Tottenham: Blades end losing run to strengthen top six bid|website=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/52072984|access-date=3 July 2020}}</ref>

On 17 December 2020, Berge suffered an injury in a 3–2 loss to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55436137|title=Sheffield United: Sander Berge injury a 'huge blow' but Lundstram expected to stay|date=24 December 2020|access-date=24 December 2023|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> which led to him missing the majority of the [[2020–21 Premier League]] season as Sheffield United were relegated to the [[EFL Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3505796/2022/08/15/sheffield-united-would-struggle-to-replace-sander-berge-and-thats-their-dilemma/|title=Sheffield United would struggle to replace Sander Berge – and that's their dilemma|date=15 August 2022|website=The Athletic}}</ref>

During the [[2022–23 Sheffield United F.C. season|2022–23 season]], Berge contributed six goals as Sheffield United were promoted back to the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3587430|title=Adrian Clarke analyses the attributes of a pair of stars who will be vital to the Blades' ambitions this season|date=1 August 2023|publisher=Premier League}}</ref>

===Burnley===
[[File:Sander Berge 23122023.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Berge pictured with a fan during his time at [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in 2023.]]

On 9 August 2023, Berge signed for Premier League club [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Clarets secure Berge signing |url=https://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/content/clarets-secure-berge |publisher=Burnley F.C. |access-date=9 August 2023 |date=9 August 2023 }}</ref> Two days later, he made his debut for the team in their 3–0 loss to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the opening game of the [[2023–24 Premier League|2023–24 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2023/aug/11/burnley-v-manchester-city-premier-league-season-kicks-off-live-score-updates|title=Burnley 0–3 Manchester City: Premier League – as it happened|date=12 August 2023|website=The Guardian}}</ref> His first goal for the club came in a 4–0 [[2023–24 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] win over [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]] on 26 September 2023.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/content/berge-praises-squads-salford-performance|title=BERGE PRAISES SQUAD'S SALFORD PERFORMANCE|date=27 September 2023|publisher=Burnley F.C.}}</ref>

Berge scored his first Premier League goal for Burnley in a 2–0 win at [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 23 December 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67812766|title=Fulham 0–2 Burnley: Wilson Odobert and Sander Berge secure third Premier League win for Clarets|date=24 December 2023|website=BBC Sport}}{{Dead link|date=September 2025 |bot=InternetArchiveBot }}</ref>

===Fulham===
[[File:Sander Berge 13092025 (1).jpg|thumb|left|200px|Berge with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in 2025.]]

On 22 August 2024, Berge signed for [[Premier League]] side [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on a five-year deal for £20&nbsp;million plus £5&nbsp;million in add-ons.<ref>{{Cite news |date=22 August 2024 |title=Fulham sign Burnley midfielder Berge for £25m |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cze5re18rw4o |access-date=22 August 2024 |publisher=BBC}}</ref> The club has the option to extend his contract by 12 months within the deal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Berge Joins Fulham |url=https://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2024/august/22/berge-joins-fulham/ |website=Fulham FC |date=22 August 2024 |access-date=22 August 2024}}</ref>

==International career==
Berge made his debut for Norway when he played for the under-15 team against Canada U15 on 2 May 2013. He has since represented Norway at every level up to the senior national team. He made his senior international debut on 23 March 2017, aged 19, coming on as a substitute in the 76th minute of the Euro-qualifier against [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fotball.no/fotballdata/person/profil/?fiksId=2768431|title=Sander Gard Bolin Berge – Profil |publisher=Norwegian Football Federation}}</ref>

On 5 September 2019, Berge scored his first senior international goal in the 34th minute of a game against [[Malta national football team|Malta]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]] rounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/match/2026170--norway-vs-malta/|title=Norway-Malta|publisher=UEFA|date=5 September 2019|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Berge comes from a basketball-playing family, with his father, Swedish mother and older brother all having played basketball at international level. His brother has also played for top flight teams [[Centrum Tigers]] and [[Asker Aliens]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv2.no/a/9013131/|title=- Til tider har jeg pushet Sander litt for hardt|first=TV 2|last=AS|date=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg.no/sport/fotball/landslaget/sander-berge-og-storebroren-storspiller-i-hver-sin-idrett/a/24149144/|title = Sander Berge og storebroren storspiller i hver sin idrett|website=Vg.no| date=26 September 2017 }}</ref> Berge is also the grandson of [[Ragnar Berge]], who played as a left-back for Vålerenga from 1945 until 1957, and was capped once by [[Norway national football team|Norway]] (in 1955).<ref>[http://www.vif-fotball.no/latest-news/article/1nga9zhr5epwv1s99l7kev32i0/title/tilbakeblikket I bestefars fotspor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201135218/http://www.vif-fotball.no/latest-news/article/1nga9zhr5epwv1s99l7kev32i0/title/tilbakeblikket |date=1 February 2016 }}, ''Vålerenga Fotball'' (10 February 2015) {{in lang|no}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Happy Constitution Day Norway! My grandfather played for Norway 65 years ago, proud to follow in the footstep of him and represent this beautiful country today🇧🇻 Stay Safe! #hurra |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/CASH_NRj6UH/?igsh=cjc2bGxzZ2puZXB6 |access-date=19 March 2024 |website=instagram}}</ref>

Berge and his partner Julie Karlsen's first child, a son, was born on 8 June 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Arntzen |first=Mats |last2=Lokøy |first2=Christian Dehlie |last3=Delebekk (foto) |first3=Bjørn S. |date=2025-06-09 |title=Landet i natt: Sander Berge har blitt far og er klar til Estland-kampen |url=https://www.vg.no/sport/i/kwgkWQ/norge-estland-sander-berge-har-blitt-far-og-er-klar-til-estland-kampen |access-date=2025-06-24 |website=VG |language=no}}</ref>

